comment: The discussion here and elsewhere where you analyze the source of the entitlement/narcissism behavior from family dynamics is interesting. Development gets arrested during development when one is made to feel powerless with abuse, when overwhelmed beyond the ability to process what happened. I think development can also be arrested when a child is given too much power, also causing overwhelm for processing. When a child experiences both sides of power imbalance, I think it produces the most intense entitlement. When someone is only beat down, the result is different. There has to be a way they learned to re-gain power through inappropriately dominating behaviors. A simple example is the neglected child who throws a tantrum and gets presents. The neglect fuels the anger, and the positive reinforcement of presents makes the tantrum reinforced from both directions. The same can be true of an abused child who bullies siblings or pets to regain power, or a parent who molests a child, but gives them power over the other parent in decisions. Both dysfunctions have to be addressed. The do have to stop being given too much power as well as addressing the abuse and powerlessness.
